Q. How often were you washed or cleaned? A. We used to sluice our faces in the morning - our linen was changed sometimes once a fortnight or three weeks;
Mary Harford
took in the milk that was used in the house - half a pint was all that was taken in in the morning; a halfpenny worth was taken out of it for their afternoon tea, and the rest was divided among us.

Cross-examined Q. Are they right and left shoes? A. No; this one has been worn on the left foot - it is a common size; Sturdy kept out of the way till the second day; I think there had been no rain at that time; the shoes were quite dry;
William Hopkins
is the young man I mistook Williams for; I did not stop the bundle at first - it was in a shawl handkerchief, and appeared like linen, but it was wrapped up.

Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. Did you ever tell any body that you made this chisel? A. No, I never said I made the jemmy; I never said so to this young man (
John Griffiths
) - I have had conversation with him many times; I never said there was a jemmy produced, and that I knew more about the transaction than any one else - he never said to me,"You made this jemmy," nor did I answer I did - I have knwon him before; he is a particular friend of mine.
